Web Sources:

    HTML Cheat Sheet – GeeksforGeeks
    A quick guide to all the basic HTML tags you'll need to build a webpage. Great for beginners who want to learn or review HTML fast.
    https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/html/html-cheat-sheet/
    
    CSS Cheat Sheet - A Basic Guide to CSS – GeeksforGeeks 
    A basic yet thorough guide to CSS properties and usage. Great for quick lookups and learning foundational styling techniques.
    https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/css/css-cheat-sheet-a-basic-guide-to-css/

Printable Sources: 

    HTML Cheatsheet – Stanford.edu https://web.stanford.edu/group/csp/cs21/htmlcheatsheet.pdf
    A printable reference sheet summarizing essential HTML tags and structure. Useful for quick offline access.
    https://web.stanford.edu/group/csp/cs21/htmlcheatsheet.pdf
    
    The Complete HTML Cheat Sheet – Hostinger Tutorials 
    A detailed PDF covering HTML elements, attributes, and examples. Designed for both learning and revision.
    https://www3.cs.stonybrook.edu/~pramod.ganapathi/doc/CSE102/CSE102-CheatSheetHTML.pdf
    
    CSS Cheatsheet (CSS 1 & 2) – Stanford.edu
    A concise guide to CSS1 and CSS2 syntax and properties. Helpful for understanding legacy and foundational CSS.
    https://web.stanford.edu/group/csp/cs21/csscheatsheet.pdf
    
    CSS Cheat Sheet – Washington.edu
    A student-friendly CSS reference from a university course. Covers common styling rules and layout techniques.
    https://courses.cs.washington.edu/courses/cse154/14sp/cheat-sheets/css-cheat-sheet.pdf

    CSS Cheat Sheet - Leslie Franke
    A visual guide to CSS that shows you how to style your website. Simple and helpful for beginners.
    https://www.lesliefranke.com/files/reference/csscheatsheet.pdf
    
Tutorials and Guidebooks

    HTML – W3Schools
    An interactive tutorial covering HTML basics to advanced topics. Includes examples and a built-in code editor.
    https://www.w3schools.com/html/

    HTML & CSS Guidebook – Josiah Spence
    A structured guidebook offering in-depth explanations of HTML and CSS. Suitable for self-paced learning.
    https://htmlandcssguidebook.com/

    HTML Complete Guide – GeeksforGeeks
    A full-spectrum HTML tutorial covering everything from tags to forms. Ideal for learners seeking structured progression.
    https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/html/html-complete-guide/

    HTML – Codecademy
    A documentation-style resource with definitions and examples of HTML elements. Great for quick reference.
    https://www.codecademy.com/resources/docs/html

    CSS Tutorial – W3Schools
    A beginner-friendly CSS tutorial with interactive examples. Covers styling, layout, and responsive design.
    https://www.w3schools.com/Css/

    HTML CSS – W3Schools
    A combined guide showing how HTML and CSS work together. Useful for understanding integration and styling.
    https://www.w3schools.com/html/html_css.asp

    The Complete HTML Cheat Sheet – Hostinger
    A downloadable PDF summarizing HTML syntax and usage. Handy for offline study and revision
    https://assets.hostinger.com/content/tutorials/pdf/HTML-Cheatsheet.pdf

HTML and CSS code validators (free and open-source)

    W3C Markup Validation Service - https://validator.w3.org/
    What it does: Checks HTML, XHTML, and other markup languages for syntax errors.
    Why it's great for students: It's the official validator from the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), easy to use, and supports direct input, file upload, or URL validation. 
    
    W3C CSS Validation Service - jigsaw.w3.org/css-validator
    What it does: Validates CSS stylesheets for errors and compatibility.
    Why it's great for students: Also from W3C, it helps students understand CSS standards and best practices.

    FreeFormatter HTML Validator - freeformatter.com/html-validator.html
    What it does: Simple tool for checking HTML code.
    Why it's great for students: Clean interface and easy to use for quick checks.

    Total Validator (Desktop App) - totalvalidator.com
    What it does: Offers both online and downloadable tools for validating HTML, CSS, accessibility, and broken links.
    Why it's great for students: Useful for offline work and more comprehensive testing.

Miscellaneous

    How to Structure HTML for Accessibility - GeeksforGeeks
    This article shows how to organize your HTML so that people with disabilities can use your website more easily. It’s a great way to learn how to make your websites more inclusive.
    https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/html/how-to-structure-your-html-properly-for-web-accessibility/

    Accessibility Tutorial - W3Schools
    A beginner-friendly tutorial that explains how to make websites easier to use for everyone, including people with disabilities. It includes examples and tips you can try right away.
    https://www.w3schools.com/accessibility/index.php
    
    Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) – Mendel Rosenblum
    A PDF from a college class that explains how CSS works. It’s a bit more advanced but still useful for learning.
    https://web.stanford.edu/class/cs142/lectures/CSS.pdf

    HTML & CSS cheatsheets – codecademy.com
    Multiple colorful and easy-to-read cheatsheets covering HTML and CSS. Great for quick reminders or explanations while coding. 
    https://www.codecademy.com/resources/cheatsheets/language/html-css

    Learn HTML - Codecademy
    This free online course teaches you how to build websites using HTML. It’s interactive and beginner-friendly, making it perfect for high school students who want to learn by doing.
    https://www.codecademy.com/learn/learn-html

    HTML & CSS Cheatsheets - Codecademy
    A colorful and easy-to-read reference sheet that shows the most common HTML and CSS tags and rules. Great for quick reminders while you're coding.
    https://www.codecademy.com/resources/cheatsheets/language/html-css
